Trust in Government and Electoral Participation in the Arab World: Evidence from the Arab Barometer

Author

Houda ES-SQALLI

Published

February 16, 2026

1 Research Question and Motivation

Trust in government is a central component of institutional legitimacy. In this report, trust is understood as citizensâ subjective assessment of the governmentâs reliability and its ability to act in the public interest. Existing research generally suggests that higher levels of institutional trust are associated with greater electoral participation (Levi & Stoker, 2000; Norris, 2011).

In the Arab world, however, this relationship may be less straightforward, as electoral participation occurs in political contexts where institutional legitimacy is often contested.

This report therefore asks: Do individuals who report having voted express higher levels of trust in the national government than those who abstained? Using data from Wave VII of the Arab Barometer, the analysis examines this association across twelve Arab countries.

To test this hypothesis, I estimate a linear probability model (OLS) in which turnout is regressed on institutional trust, controlling for age and including country fixed effects. Coefficients are interpreted as average percentage-point changes in the probability of reporting having voted (Verba, Schlozman & Brady, 1995).

2 Hypothesis

Building on research linking institutional trust to political participation, this report formulates the following hypothesis:

H1: Individuals with higher levels of trust in the national government are more likely to report having voted in the most recent national election.

This expectation follows the idea that institutional trust can reduce the perceived costs of participation and strengthen the belief that elections are meaningful channels of political influence (Levi & Stoker, 2000; Norris, 2011). Citizens who view governing institutions as reliable and responsive may therefore be more inclined to engage electorally.

At the same time, the trustâturnout relationship may be less straightforward in the Arab world, where voting can also reflect protest, strategic behavior, or social pressure rather than institutional support (Hirschman, 1970). The empirical association thus remains theoretically ambiguous and requires systematic examination across countries.

This hypothesis concerns association, not causation.

3 Data Source

This analysis uses data from Wave VII of the Arab Barometer (2021â2022), a comparative survey conducted across twelve countries in the Middle East and North Africa: Algeria, Egypt, Iraq, Jordan, Kuwait, Lebanon, Libya, Mauritania, Morocco, Palestine, Sudan, and Tunisia. The data were collected using stratified probabilistic sampling, primarily through face-to-face computer-assisted interviews (CAPI) (Arab Barometer, Technical Report).

National sample sizes generally range from approximately 1,300 to 2,500 respondents depending on the country.

Pooling countries in this way makes it possible to examine the average association between trust in government and electoral participation across the region. To account for contextual differences between national settings, the analysis includes country fixed effects in the statistical models.

3.1 Variables Used

  • Trust in the national government (Q201A_1): an ordinal variable measured on a four-point scale,ranging from 1 = âa great deal of trustâ to 4 = âno trust at all.â For ease of interpretation, the scale is reversed in the analysis so that higher values correspond to higher levels of trust.

  • Electoral participation (Q301A): a binary variable indicating whether the respondent reports having voted in the most recent national election (1 = voted, 0 = did not vote).

In the analysis, electoral participation constitutes the main dependent variable, while trust in government is the central explanatory variable. Control variables, such as age and cross-national variation, are also taken into account.

Responses coded as âDonât knowâ or âRefusedâ were excluded from the analysis (see Data Cleaning).

5 Data Cleaning

Responses coded as âDonât knowâ (98) or âRefusedâ (99) were excluded from the analytic sample. The analysis is therefore restricted to respondents with valid information on both electoral participation (Q301A) and trust in the national government (Q201A_1).

The resulting dataset corresponds to a complete-case sample for the main variables of interest.

# Number of observations before cleaning
n_before <- nrow(data)

# Construct analytic dataset (complete-case on turnout and trust)
clean <- data %>%
  
  # Keep only valid responses for turnout and trust
  filter(
    Q301A %in% c(1, 2),
    Q201A_1 %in% c(1, 2, 3, 4),
    !is.na(Q1001),     # keep only respondents with age
    !is.na(COUNTRY)    # keep only respondents with country
  ) %>%
  
  mutate(
    # Outcome variable: turnout (factor for descriptives)
    voted = factor(
      ifelse(Q301A == 1, "Voted", "Abstained"),
      levels = c("Abstained", "Voted")
    ),

    # Outcome variable: turnout (binary for regression)
    vote_binary = ifelse(Q301A == 1, 1, 0),

    # Main predictor: reverse trust scale so higher values = more trust
    trust = 5 - Q201A_1,

    # Trust categories (original wording, ordered low â high for plots)
    trust_label = factor(
  trust,
  levels = c(1, 2, 3, 4),
  labels = c(
    "No trust at all",
    "Not a lot of trust",
    "Quite a lot of trust",
    "A great deal of trust"
  ),
  ordered = TRUE
),

    # Control variable: age
    age = as.numeric(Q1001),

    # Country fixed effects
    country = factor(COUNTRY)
  )

# Number of observations after cleaning
n_after <- nrow(clean)

# Percentage excluded
percent_removed <- round((n_before - n_after) / n_before * 100, 1)

# Summary table of the cleaning process
cleaning_summary <- data.frame(
  "N before" = n_before,
  "N after" = n_after,
  "% excluded" = percent_removed,
  check.names = FALSE
)

kable(
  cleaning_summary,
  caption = "Table 1. Sample size before and after data cleaning"
) %>%
  kable_styling(full_width = FALSE)
Table 1. Sample size before and after data cleaning
N before N after % excluded
26154 20034 23.4

Before cleaning, the dataset includes N = 26,154 observations. After excluding missing or non-informative responses, the final analytic sample contains N = 20,034, corresponding to a reduction of 6,120 observations (-23.4%). This relatively large proportion of excluded cases should be kept in mind, as non-response may introduce bias if it is not random.

7 Descriptive Statistics

Before turning to inferential models, I first describe the distribution of the main outcome (turnout) and the key explanatory variable (trust in government).

7.1 Distribution of Electoral Participation (Outcome)

Figure 1 displays the distribution of self-reported electoral participation in the analytic sample. Because turnout constitutes the outcome variable in this report, it is important to first document how many respondents report voting versus abstaining before examining its relationship with institutional trust.

Figure 1 shows that self-reported turnout is relatively evenly split between respondents who declare having voted (48.2%) and those who report abstaining (51.8%). As in most survey-based studies of electoral participation, these figures may overestimate actual turnout due to social desirability bias, whereby some individuals are more likely to report voting than non-participation.

Reported turnout also varies substantially across countries in the analytic sample, ranging from approximately 32.7% to 72.2%. This cross-national dispersion likely reflects both differences in electoral context and potential reporting biases, and it should be kept in mind when interpreting the subsequent association between institutional trust and voting behavior.

Table 4 shows that respondents who reported voting display slightly higher trust on average (M = 2.01) than those who abstained (M = 1.91). However, descriptive patterns do not provide information about statistical uncertainty or robustness. The next section therefore evaluates this association using inferential models that account for age and cross-national differences.

8 Limits of descriptive statistics

Descriptive analyses are useful for identifying patterns in the sample, but they provide no measure of statistical uncertainty. The differences observed between voters and non-voters could partly reflect random sampling variation and may not necessarily generalize to the broader population.

In addition, electoral participation is measured through self-reports and may therefore be affected by social desirability bias and measurement error. Finally, trust in government is captured using a four-category ordinal scale, which limits the precision with which it can be treated as a fully continuous measure.

Reported turnout in survey data often exceeds official electoral participation rates, suggesting possible over-reporting due to social desirability bias. Turnout should therefore be interpreted as self-reported participation rather than validated voting behavior.

For these reasons, the next section relies on inferential statistical models to formally test the association between institutional trust and turnout, while accounting for relevant control variables.

9 Inferential Analysis: Testing Hypothesis H1

The descriptive statistics presented above suggest a modest positive association between trust in government and self-reported electoral participation. However, descriptive comparisons alone cannot assess whether this relationship is statistically distinguishable from zero in the broader population.

This section therefore uses inferential statistics to formally test Hypothesis H1:

H1: Individuals who report higher trust in the national government are more likely to report having voted.

10 Statistical model

The dependent variable is electoral turnout, coded as a binary indicator:

  • vote_binary = 1 if the respondent reports having voted
  • vote_binary = 0 otherwise

Because the outcome is dichotomous, the standard modeling strategy would be logistic regression. However, the main analysis estimates a Linear Probability Model (LPM), which applies ordinary least squares to a binary dependent variable.

The advantage of the LPM is interpretability: coefficients can be read directly as percentage-point changes in the probability of voting. For example, a coefficient of 0.03 corresponds to a 3-point increase in turnout probability.

A known limitation is that errors are heteroskedastic by construction when the dependent variable is binary. Therefore, all models report heteroskedasticity-robust standard errors (HC1).

11 Control variables and identification strategy

Two key factors may confound the relationship between trust and turnout:

  • Age, since electoral participation is strongly structured by the life cycle.
    Across democracies worldwide, younger citizens consistently report lower turnout rates than older cohorts, making youth abstention a well-established feature of electoral behavior (Franklin, 2004; Blais, 2006). Moreover, institutional trust may also vary systematically across generations, failing to adjust for age could bias the estimated association between trust and voting.
  • Country context, because the Arab Barometer pools respondents from multiple national settings with very different baseline turnout levels and institutional environments.

To ensure that the estimated trustâturnout association is not driven by cross-national differences, the models include country fixed effects. This means the coefficient on trust is identified from within-country comparisons between individuals living in the same national context, rather than being driven by differences across political systems.

11.1 Model 1: Baseline association between trust and turnout

This first model provides a baseline test of Hypothesis H1 by estimating the unconditional relationship between trust in the national government and self-reported turnout.

Turnout is coded as a binary outcome:

  • vote_binary = 1 if the respondent reports having voted
  • vote_binary = 0 otherwise

Because the dependent variable is dichotomous, the model is estimated as a Linear Probability Model (LPM). Coefficients can therefore be interpreted directly as percentage-point changes in the probability of voting.

11.1.1 Estimation

# Model 1: Baseline LPM
model1 <- lm(vote_binary ~ trust, data = clean)

# Robust standard errors (HC1)
coeftest(model1, vcov = vcovHC(model1, type = "HC1"))

11.2 Regression results (Model 1)

# Robust SEs (HC1)
robust_se <- sqrt(diag(vcovHC(model1, type = "HC1")))

# Build regression table
table_model1 <- tidy(model1) %>%
  mutate(
    `Robust SE` = robust_se,
    estimate    = round(estimate, 3),
    `Robust SE` = round(`Robust SE`, 3),
    p.value     = ifelse(p.value < 0.001, "<0.001",
                         round(p.value, 3)),
    term = case_when(
      term == "(Intercept)" ~ "Intercept",
      term == "trust"       ~ "Trust in government"
    )
  ) %>%
  select(term, estimate, `Robust SE`, p.value)

# Display journal-style table

11.2.1 Interpretation

Table 5 shows a positive and statistically significant association between trust in the national government and self-reported turnout. Using heteroskedasticity- robust standard errors, a one-point increase on the four-point trust scale is associated with an approximately 2.4 percentage-point increase in the probability of reporting having voted (\(\beta = 0.024\), \(p < 0.001\)).

The explanatory power of the model is very limited (RÂ² = 0.002), which is common in individual-level turnout models.

Substantively, this indicates that trust in government alone explains only a very small fraction of the individual variation in turnout. This suggests that many other determinants of voting behavior â such as education, political interest, or mobilization are not captured in this simple specification.

Overall, this baseline result provides preliminary support for Hypothesis H1, although the estimated association remains substantively modest.

This association should be interpreted as descriptive rather than causal.

11.3 Model diagnostics (Model 1)

# Residuals vs fitted values (heteroskedasticity)
plot(model1, which = 1)

Figure 4 illustrates the residual structure of the baseline linear probability model. As expected with a binary dependent variable, heteroskedasticity is inherent, which motivates the use of robust (HC1) standard errors throughout.

11.4 Model 2: Controlling for age and country fixed effects

Model 2 extends the baseline specification by adjusting for age and country-level differences in electoral participation. Turnout is strongly structured by the life cycle: younger citizens consistently participate less than older cohorts, and institutional trust may also vary systematically across generations. Controlling for age therefore helps reduce potential confounding in the trustâturnout relationship.

In addition, the Arab Barometer pools respondents from multiple national contexts with very different baseline turnout rates and institutional environments. Model 2 therefore includes country fixed effects, meaning that the coefficient on trust is identified from within-country comparisons between individuals living in the same national setting.

Robust standard errors (HC1) are reported throughout.

11.4.1 Estimation

# Model 2: LPM with controls and country fixed effects
model2 <- lm(vote_binary ~ trust + age + factor(country), data = clean)

# Robust standard errors (HC1)
coeftest(model2, vcov = vcovHC(model2, type = "HC1"))

11.6 Interpretation

Model 2 shows that trust in government remains positively and statistically significantly associated with self-reported turnout after adjusting for age and country fixed effects (\(\beta = 0.033\), \(p < 0.001\)).

In the linear probability framework, this implies that a one-point increase on the four-point trust scale is associated with an approximately 3.3 percentage- point increase in the probability of reporting having voted.

Model fit remains modest (RÂ² = 0.059), which is common in individual-level turnout models.

This value suggests that, even after controlling for age and country fixed effects, most of the variation in self-reported turnout remains unexplained, highlighting the multifactorial nature of electoral participation.

Because country fixed effects are included, this estimate is identified from within-country comparisons rather than cross-national differences.

Overall, these results support Hypothesis H1, but they should be interpreted as an association rather than evidence of a causal effect.

11.7 Model diagnostics (Model 2)

# Residuals vs fitted values (linearity / heteroskedasticity)
plot(model2, which = 1)

Figure 5 illustrates the expected heteroskedastic residual pattern in a linear probability model. Because turnout is a binary dependent variable, residual normality is not a substantively relevant assumption. The main concern is heteroskedasticity, which is inherent when modeling a dichotomous outcome with OLS. Therefore, all reported standard errors are heteroskedasticity-robust (HC1).

In addition, the logistic regression robustness check confirms that the substantive conclusions do not depend on the LPM specification.

11.8 Robustness check: Logistic regression

Because turnout is a binary outcome, I also estimate a logistic regression model as a robustness check. The results are substantively similar: trust remains positively and statistically significantly associated with the probability of reporting having voted. This suggests that the main conclusions are not driven by the linear probability specification.

# Logistic regression robustness check
logit2 <- glm(
  vote_binary ~ trust + age + factor(country),
  data = clean,
  family = binomial
)

# Build clean regression table (Odds Ratios only)
tbl_logit <- tidy(logit2) %>%
  filter(term %in% c("trust", "age")) %>%
  mutate(
    Odds_Ratio = round(exp(estimate), 2),
    p.value = ifelse(p.value < 0.001, "<0.001", round(p.value, 3)),

    term = case_when(
      term == "trust" ~ "Trust in government",
      term == "age"   ~ "Age (years)"
    )
  ) %>%
  select(term, Odds_Ratio, p.value)

# Display clean table
kable(
  tbl_logit,
  col.names = c("Predictor", "Odds Ratio", "P-value"),
  caption = "Table 7. Logistic regression robustness check (odds ratios)",
  booktabs = TRUE
) %>%
  kable_styling(full_width = FALSE)
Table 7. Logistic regression robustness check (odds ratios)
Predictor Odds Ratio P-value
Trust in government 1.15 <0.001
Age (years) 1.00 0.038

Accordingly, the LPM provides a reasonable approximation for interpreting effect sizes in percentage-point terms. The logistic regression confirms the same substantive conclusion, indicating that the positive association is robust to model specification.

11.9 Robustness check: Trust as an ordinal categorical predictor

Trust is measured on a four-point ordinal scale. Treating it as continuous in the LPM assumes equal distances between categories, which may be imperfect. As an additional robustness check, I estimate a model treating trust as a categorical predictor. This allows the effect of each trust level to be compared without imposing linearity.

# Step 1: Recreate trust as a fully unordered categorical variable
# (this prevents R from using polynomial contrasts such as .L, .Q, .C)
clean$trust_cat <- factor(
  as.character(clean$trust_label),
  levels = c(
    "No trust at all",
    "Not a lot of trust",
    "Quite a lot of trust",
    "A great deal of trust"
  ),
  ordered = FALSE
)

# Step 2: Set the baseline (reference) category for interpretation
# All coefficients will be interpreted relative to "No trust at all"
clean$trust_cat <- relevel(clean$trust_cat, ref = "No trust at all")

# Step 3: Estimate a logistic regression model
# Controls: age + country fixed effects
model3 <- glm(
  vote_binary ~ trust_cat + age + factor(country),
  data = clean,
  family = binomial
)

# Step 4: Display results in a clean regression table
# - Convert coefficients into odds ratios for easier interpretation
# - Format p-values properly (avoid showing "0")
tbl_model3 <- tidy(model3) %>%
  filter(grepl("trust_cat", term)) %>%
  mutate(
    Odds_Ratio = round(exp(estimate), 2),
    p.value = ifelse(p.value < 0.001, "<0.001", round(p.value, 3)),
    estimate = round(estimate, 3),
    std.error = round(std.error, 3),

    # Clean term names for readability in the table
    term = case_when(
      term == "trust_catNot a lot of trust" ~ "Not a lot of trust",
      term == "trust_catQuite a lot of trust" ~ "Quite a lot of trust",
      term == "trust_catA great deal of trust" ~ "A great deal of trust"
    )
  ) %>%
  select(term, Odds_Ratio, p.value)

# Step 5: Print the final table
kable(
  tbl_model3,
  caption = "Table 8. Logistic regression treating trust as a categorical predictor (reference: No trust at all)"
) %>%
  kable_styling(full_width = FALSE)
Table 8. Logistic regression treating trust as a categorical predictor (reference: No trust at all)
term Odds_Ratio p.value
Not a lot of trust 1.25 <0.001
Quite a lot of trust 1.45 <0.001
A great deal of trust 1.36 <0.001

Table 8 re-estimates the relationship between institutional trust and turnout by treating trust as a categorical variable rather than imposing a linear structure. Respondents reporting no trust at all serve as the reference category.

Relative to this group, individuals expressing higher levels of trust are significantly more likely to report having voted. In particular, those reporting quite a lot of trust exhibit substantially higher odds of turnout (OR = 1.45, p < 0.001). Respondents reporting a great deal of trust also show increased participation odds (OR = 1.36, p < 0.001).

For instance, an odds ratio of 1.45 implies that respondents reporting quite a lot of trust have approximately 45% higher odds of voting compared to those reporting no trust at all, holding age and country constant.

Overall, these findings show that the positive association between institutional trust and self-reported turnout remains when trust is modeled using discrete categories in a logistic regression framework. This suggests that the relationship is not solely an artifact of imposing linearity on the four-point scale.

11.10 Conclusion: Does the evidence support H1?

Across both the linear probability and logistic regression specifications, institutional trust is consistently associated with a higher likelihood of reporting having voted.

Taken together, the regression evidence supports Hypothesis H1, although the estimated relationship is modest in substantive terms and should be interpreted as an association rather than a causal effect.

11.11 Limitations and scope

Several limitations should be considered when interpreting these findings.

  • Self-reported turnout may be affected by social desirability bias, leading respondents to overstate electoral participation.

  • The analysis is observational, so the estimated relationships cannot be interpreted causally and may reflect reverse causation or unobserved confounding factors.

  • The analysis includes only a limited set of individual-level controls (age and country fixed effects). Other important determinants of electoral participation â such as education, political interest, income, or political mobilization â are not included in this specification. As a result, the estimated association between trust and turnout may partly reflect omitted variable bias.

  • The pooled cross-national design may mask substantial heterogeneity across countries, since the meaning of both trust and voting varies across political contexts.

  • Institutional trust is measured on an ordinal survey scale, raising concerns about measurement comparability across settings.

Future research could estimate country-specific models and incorporate additional political and socioeconomic controls to better account for contextual variation.

The purpose of this report is therefore not to provide a fully saturated model of turnout, but to offer a focused first test of the bivariate trustâturnout relationship in a comparative Arab context.
